CHAPTER-2 HANDS-ON learning

Topics, are similar to tables in the DB, to store data related to a particular subject. Kafka doesn't enforce schema, the onus is upon the user to do that.
To create a topic, use kafka-topics.sh, specify the partition and replication factor over here. For now its just 1.

- Kafka-consumer won't display messages, as it reads the topic at the end, to display messages use the flag --from-beginning
- kafka-console-producer.sh to create the message. 
- The common thread between consumer and producer is the topic name, this topic name clubs the consumers and producers into a group implicitly. And, there won't be cross contamination from other producers.
- You can have multiple producers and consumers to either write and read the data, for that topic. 
- Replication factor-1 means if a server is dead or down, your topic is unavailable, to ensure fault-tolerance, keep it above 1, depending on the brokers.

